If I upload a plain text file with a .txt extension and then click on it in the attachments tab, I get a reponse with "Content-Type: application/x-httpd-cgi" rather than "text/plain". Firefox opens a save as dialog. Internet Explorer displays the contents inline -- but without any line breaks...

The following code produces strange output:

|| Heading 1 ||
| {panel}{code:none}
{panel}
|| A 1 ||
| b |
{panel}
{code}{panel} |

|| Heading 1 ||
| {panel}{code:none}
{panel}
\|\| A 1 \|\|
\| b \|
{panel}
{code}{panel} |

How it is rendered is documented in the screenshot. Especially strange, I think, is the &124; output.

In fact this example is stupid but I think it might be the source of a problem I had where the outer {panel}-macro was in fact a user-macro which renders its contents, which produces other strange result.

The expected output of at least the first example should be similar to the result of rendering this:

|| Heading 1 ||
| {code:none}
{panel}
|| A 1 ||
| b |
{panel}
{code} |

which indeed renders a table-cell with a code-block documenting how to write a table.

